city.name: County Dublin
city.about: '''County Dublin''' (''Contae Bhaile Átha Cliath'') is a historic county surrounding Dublin city in the Republic of Ireland, with a population of 1.5 million in 2022. It was abolished as an administrative or political unit in 1994, with its territory allocated to four new entities. Nevertheless it still coheres as a destination for travellers, in two ways: for the city to escape to the surrounds, for instance to the seaside at Howth or the races at Leopardstown; and for visitors to stay here and day-trip into Dublin while avoiding the city's congestion and high prices.

points_of_interest.name: Harbour Bar
points_of_interest.description: Famous pub so it's on the tourist circuit, but deservedly so - the Harbour scores highly for drink, food, service and ambiance. It's a knock-through of a row of fishermen's cottages, so it has a series of rooms each with their own character: main bar, snug, live lounge, good room, beer garden, and upstairs. Often has live music, dog-friendly.

points_of_interest.name: Duff's
points_of_interest.description: No televisions and a great quiet pint among cycling memorabilia.

points_of_interest.name: Abbey Tavern
points_of_interest.description: Trad pub with authentic fireplace and decent food. Occasional live music.

points_of_interest.name: The Two Foxes
points_of_interest.description: O'Neill's Good pub with liv music.

points_of_interest.name: Dunphy's
points_of_interest.description: Traditional central pub.

points_of_interest.name: McLouglin's
points_of_interest.description: Old style bar with live TV sports. Upstairs is an Indian restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: Central Lounge - Mrs O's
points_of_interest.description: formerly Fannings Friendly pub with snooker / pool tables.

points_of_interest.name: The Cock Tavern
points_of_interest.description: It's been a pub since the 18th century. Done out in old-world style with slated floors, old oak and pine beams fused together with brick and granite walls and warm wooden floors. And good beer, food an atmosphere as well.

points_of_interest.name: The Pound & The Attic
points_of_interest.description: This pub has great atmosphere with food served all day and live music Saturday nights. The Pound was the adjacent land where stray animals were held, cos there wasn't enough room in the Attic.

points_of_interest.name: Wrights Cafe Bar
points_of_interest.description: The upper level lounge, with dramatic red and cream furniture, dark wood tables and chandeliers, gives a distinctive ‘bordello’ effect. Behind the bar, there’s a secluded lounge that overlooks an open-plan area below, complete with a stage for dancing to live music. Dog friendly.
points_of_interest.address: The Plaza, Malahide Rd K67 VW44
points_of_interest.hours: Su-Tu noon-10PM, W Th noon-11:30PM, F Sa noon-2:30AM

points_of_interest.name: The Coachman's Inn
points_of_interest.description: Bar and grill, good Sunday carvery.

points_of_interest.name: Peadar Kearney's
points_of_interest.description: Named for Peadar Ó Cearnaígh (1883-1942) who penned ''Amhráin na bhFiann'', Ireland's national anthem, and was uncle to the three Behans, authors and prolific drinkers all. The pub is a great spot for pre- and post-gig drinks next to Olympia Theatre, with a young crowd and live music from up and coming Irish trad bands. Mostly tourists here but a nice spot to talk to other visitors.

points_of_interest.name: The Cobblestone
points_of_interest.description: They describe themselves as "a drinking pub with a music problem" and have nightly trad sessions.

points_of_interest.name: Frank Ryans
points_of_interest.description: This pub and pizzeria has friendly bar staff and a mixed crowd of students, law types, trendies and locals. Expect weekly trad nights interspersed with Rockabilly, Country and Soul on the jukebox.

points_of_interest.name: O'Donoghue's
points_of_interest.description: With two bars across a courtyard, it's famous for impromptu live music, and where folk group The Dubliners were formed. They have rooms.

points_of_interest.name: The Barge
points_of_interest.description: McCafferty's Friendly trad pub with four areas, good food and great decor.

points_of_interest.name: Hartigan's
points_of_interest.description: Popular student bar, good choice after international rugby matches.

points_of_interest.name: The Brazen Head
points_of_interest.description: Surely the oldest pub in Dublin, founded in 1198 - Ireland's oldest, in Athlone, is from 900 AD. Wonderful on warm, dry summer nights. Live trad music and friendly atmosphere. One of the bars is covered in signed currency notes, there's quite a collection but lacking any bitcoins.

points_of_interest.name: Ned O'Shea's
points_of_interest.description: Decent food and live music and dancing. Ned O’Shea (1937-2018) was a famous trad musician from Kerry.

points_of_interest.name: John Fallon's
points_of_interest.description: Capstan Bar Small friendly local pub.

points_of_interest.name: The Oval
points_of_interest.description: Good for drink and food, does an excellent Irish stew. Attracts a mixed age group. Lots of pictures of old Irish celebrities with a tribute to the Quiet Man.

points_of_interest.name: John Kavanagh's
points_of_interest.description: The Gravediggers Mournfully authentic pub from 1833 and little altered, where you toast the departed in the next-door cemetery.

points_of_interest.name: Bowe's Lounge Bar
points_of_interest.description: Victorian pub with a huge selection of whiskey.

points_of_interest.name: Mulligans
points_of_interest.description: Busy pub with great Guinness and plenty of history, having been frequented by James Joyce among others.

points_of_interest.name: Nancy Hands
points_of_interest.description: Family-friendly restaurant and bar by entrance to Phoenix Park.

points_of_interest.name: Ryan's
points_of_interest.description: Beautiful Victorian pub, part of Buckley Steakhouse chain. A good place for a pint or meal before getting a train out of Heuston.

points_of_interest.name: Palace Bar
points_of_interest.description: Trad bar with interesting decor complete with "snug" (small private booth). Live music upstairs.

points_of_interest.name: The Long Hall
points_of_interest.description: Atmospheric bar with Victorian decor, one of the last "long hall" bars in Ireland.
points_of_interest.address: 31 South Great Georges St D02 DV744

points_of_interest.name: Kehoe's
points_of_interest.description: An excellent spot for a pint or a meal after a days' sight-seeing or shopping. Several snugs downstairs.

points_of_interest.name: Kennedy's
points_of_interest.description: Trad-style pub serving good food and drink with plenty of friendly atmosphere.

points_of_interest.name: O'Neill's
points_of_interest.description: Excellent atmosphere in a Victorian style pub. They have great food with weekend lunchtime carvery.

points_of_interest.name: The Stag's Head
points_of_interest.description: Trad Victorian pub, no TV, just great ales and conversation.

points_of_interest.name: Dawson Lounge
points_of_interest.description: Probably Dublin's smallest pub - 20 customers and it's packed.

points_of_interest.name: McDaids
points_of_interest.description: This trad pub was a regular place for Brendan Behan and Oscar Wilde to ponder life.

points_of_interest.name: Grogan's
points_of_interest.description: Castle Lounge Wonderful trad pub, no music or TV. Great Guinness and a mixture of tourists and locals, with a hotchpotch of interesting art on the walls.

points_of_interest.name: The Bailey
points_of_interest.description: Contemporary bar with tapas, presided over by a portrait of James Joyce. Nice outdoor seating, very busy on summer afternoons and evenings.

points_of_interest.name: The Lotts
points_of_interest.description: Cafe bar, elegant interior with chandeliers, a marble bar and comfortable leather seating. Live music many nights. Small outside seating area.

points_of_interest.name: Market Bar
points_of_interest.description: Spacious bar and tapas restaurant with a good value menu.

points_of_interest.name: The Odeon
points_of_interest.description: This attractive bar at the top of Harcourt St is in a converted railway station.
points_of_interest.hours: Tu W noon-11:30PM, Th F noon-2:30AM, Sa 3PM-2:30AM

points_of_interest.name: Pygmalion
points_of_interest.description: Busy bar and restaurant with Med food, best book if you hope to eat.

points_of_interest.name: Café en Seine
points_of_interest.description: Swish megapub on 3 floors, pricey.

points_of_interest.name: Against the Grain
points_of_interest.description: Owned by a Galway brewery, this has a wide variety of Irish micro-brews and world beers. No generic commercial beers on tap. A vibrant pub with an eclectic clientele.

points_of_interest.name: Bull and Castle
points_of_interest.description: Gastropub and beer hall with a large selection of micro-brewed and international beers. Part of Buckley Steakhouse chain.

points_of_interest.name: JR Mahon's
points_of_interest.description: Spread over two stories, they produce a very good stout quite different to Guinness, fresher and more complex, plus their own ale and lager. Also has good cafeteria-style lunch.

points_of_interest.name: Porterhouse
points_of_interest.description: Indigenous brews including an oyster stout, plus an extensive Belgian and international beer list. Also does reasonably priced food. Has sister pubs on Grafton St and in Bray and Phibsboro.

points_of_interest.name: The Foggy Dew
points_of_interest.description: Popular central Victorian-styled pub.
points_of_interest.address: 1 Fownes Street, Temple Bar D02 WP21
points_of_interest.hours: M-Th noon-midnight, F Sa noon-1AM, Su 2PM-midnight

points_of_interest.name: Bruxelles
points_of_interest.description: Lively pub founded in 1886. Spread over 3 bars the music is loud and the atmosphere is buzzing. Outside is a statue of Phil Lynott, from Irish rock band Thin Lizzy. For metal, rock and indie music go downstairs.

points_of_interest.name: The Duke
points_of_interest.description: Great after-work bar and Fridays it's packed to the door.

points_of_interest.name: O'Donoghues
points_of_interest.description: A comfortable bar with live music and TV sport. It's also a hang-out spot for some of the city's most well-known musicians, actors and DJs.

points_of_interest.name: Fibber Magees
points_of_interest.description: A heavy metal bar, handy for Rotunda Hospital.

points_of_interest.name: The Workmans Club
points_of_interest.description: From 1888 to 2003 this was the city's Working Mens Club, turning into a live entertainment venue in 2010. It's on two floors, the main live room is 300 capacity and beside it is the venue bar. It's friendly, relaxing and well-run.

points_of_interest.name: The Academy
points_of_interest.description: This is primarily a live performance venue, and Friday and Saturday are clubbing nights.

points_of_interest.name: Copper Face Jacks
points_of_interest.description: Legendary club, a post-pub meat-market. Over 20s only, some of the clientele hoping to cop off are going on 120. Rooms available for private events.

points_of_interest.name: The George
points_of_interest.description: The oldest gay bar in Dublin, with late-night drag shows, karaoke, bingo and DJs.
points_of_interest.address: 89 South Great George's St D02 R220

points_of_interest.name: Aqua Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Fine dining at the end of West Pier. Seafood restaurant with lunch and à la carte menus available.

points_of_interest.name: The Coliemore
points_of_interest.description: Pub with decent food and beers. They also have accommodation.

points_of_interest.name: Daata Bray
points_of_interest.description: Good Pakistani cuisine. Tasty and reasonably priced though vegetarians have limited choice..

points_of_interest.name: Mugs Café
points_of_interest.description: Friendly place, cash only.

points_of_interest.name: Gibneys of Malahide
points_of_interest.description: Serves trad pub food M-F to 9:30PM, Sa Su to 8PM. Often has live music.

points_of_interest.name: Platform Pizza Bar
points_of_interest.description: Bright pizza place next to Daata.

points_of_interest.name: Summit Inn

points_of_interest.name: Cape Greko
points_of_interest.description: Greek and Cypriot restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: Hartley's
points_of_interest.description: Smart European restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: King Sitric

points_of_interest.name: Horse & Hound
points_of_interest.description: Popular pub-restaurant with a village vibe.

points_of_interest.name: Harvey's
points_of_interest.description: Harvest Inn Friendly bar and grill.

points_of_interest.name: Karma Thai
points_of_interest.description: Thai cuisine and sushi.

points_of_interest.name: Pappagallino's Ice Cream
points_of_interest.description: Quality Italian ice cream.

points_of_interest.name: Butlers Chocolate Café
points_of_interest.description: Coffee, cake, chocolate and light bites, whenever you're ready for a sit-down in the shopping centre.
points_of_interest.address: Swords Pavilions Shopping Centre, Malahide Rd

points_of_interest.name: Wine House Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Slick service and good Mediterranean food.

points_of_interest.name: d'Chilli Shaker
points_of_interest.description: Indian restaurant with consistently good reviews for cuisine and service.

points_of_interest.name: Indie Spice
points_of_interest.description: Good Indian restaurant, all the classics and vegetarian choices, though limited options for vegans.
points_of_interest.address: Burgundy House, Forster Way K67 E4A8

points_of_interest.name: Old Schoolhouse
points_of_interest.description: Locally-sourced steak, game and seafood are specialties. Limited menu but great quality and service, sometimes has live music. The bar has TV sports and there's a beer garden.

points_of_interest.name: Eddie Rocket's
points_of_interest.description: US retro-style chain diner: burgers, wings and similar fare.

points_of_interest.name: Gourmet Food Parlour
points_of_interest.description: Bright modern restaurant with Med-style meals.
points_of_interest.address: Unit 2 St Fintans, North St K67 P825

points_of_interest.name: UCD Village Market
points_of_interest.address: Green area between Campus Bus Park and Sutherland School of Law
points_of_interest.hours: Thursdays only during term times. Does not take place outside of term or during inclement weather

points_of_interest.name: Bewley's Café

points_of_interest.name: Butlers Chocolate Café
points_of_interest.description: Chain of chocolate-themed cafes, Wicklow Street is the original outlet. There are three others in city centre, plus airside in T1 and T2 at the airport. They also ship orders.

points_of_interest.name: Govinda's
points_of_interest.description: Hare Krishna-run vegetarian restaurant. Filling portions, only order their Special if you're really hungry.

points_of_interest.name: Pablo Picante
points_of_interest.description: Small friendly Mexican eatery, eat in or take away to nearby St Stephen's Green. They also have outlets at Clarendon Market and Dawson St.

points_of_interest.name: Zaytoon
points_of_interest.description: Casual Persian restaurant. They also have a fast-food cafe in Temple Bar (corner of Parliament St and Essex St).

points_of_interest.name: Bad Ass Café
points_of_interest.description: Modern pub and entertainment venue for US-themed food, plus trad Irish beer and live music.
points_of_interest.hours: M-Th noon-11:30PM, F noon-1:30AM, Sa Su 9AM-1:30AM

points_of_interest.name: Balfes
points_of_interest.description: Lively seafood restaurant with outdoor terrace.

points_of_interest.name: Bar Italia
points_of_interest.description: Good value Italian with great atmosphere.

points_of_interest.name: Cornucopia
points_of_interest.description: Smart modern restaurant for vegan and other wholefood options.

points_of_interest.name: Dunne & Crescenzi
points_of_interest.description: Smart trattoria, rightly popular so get there early.

points_of_interest.name: FX Buckley Steakhouse
points_of_interest.description: Quality steaks in a friendly and comfortable restaurant. Plus other meat and seafood, but not much for veggies.

points_of_interest.name: Gallagher's Boxty House
points_of_interest.description: Good traditional Irish fare and not expensive. A boxty is a traditional Irish potato pancake filled and rolled up. Also try the Irish stew and the chowder. Small, friendly, traditional Irish decor.

points_of_interest.name: Elephant & Castle
points_of_interest.description: Famous and popular for its chicken wings, you could have a long wait for a table Saturday lunchtime. It's now a national chain but this is the original outlet.

points_of_interest.name: Peploe's
points_of_interest.description: Excellent basement wine bar and bistro.

points_of_interest.name: TP Smiths
points_of_interest.description: Good pub food, handy if you're shopping around Henry Street.

points_of_interest.name: Bang Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: A great cosmopolitan menu. Not cheap, but food and presentation is excellent.

points_of_interest.name: Brasserie Sixty6
points_of_interest.description: Large, stylish modern European restaurant gets good reviews for food, service and atmosphere.
points_of_interest.address: 66 South Great Georges Street D02 YD61

points_of_interest.name: Fire Steakhouse
points_of_interest.description: Casual dining restaurant in the former Supper Room of the Lord Mayor.
points_of_interest.address: Mansion House, Dawson Street D02 AF30

points_of_interest.name: L'Gueuleton
points_of_interest.description: Pricey but highly-rated and popular place.

points_of_interest.name: Kites
points_of_interest.description: Chinese, predominantly Cantonese, also in Szechuan, Peking and Thai style, gets great reviews.

points_of_interest.name: Roly's Bistro
points_of_interest.description: Lively bistro offering set menus.

points_of_interest.name: Malahide Cricket Club
points_of_interest.description: This ground, capacity 11,500, is the home of Leinster Cricket and the usual venue for Ireland's international matches.

points_of_interest.name: UCD Woodland Walks
points_of_interest.description: There are five walking trails around the campus, between {{km|1.8}} and {{km|6.2}}. The campus has trees dating back to its use as suburban estates in the 18th and 19th centuries, supplemented by planting since the 1960s.
points_of_interest.address: Road 12, Clonskeagh, County Dublin D04, Ireland

points_of_interest.name: Balbriggan Golf Club
points_of_interest.description: Parkland 18-hole course amidst mature trees and water hazards. White tees 5893 m, par 72.

points_of_interest.name: Jameson Golf Links
points_of_interest.description: Portmarnock GC This is a links course on a sandy peninsula, part of an upmarket hotel. The championship course is 7463 yards (6824 m), par 72.
points_of_interest.address: Golf Links Rd, Stapolin D13 V2X7

points_of_interest.name: UCD Sculpture Trail
points_of_interest.description: The University College Dublin has a collection of scuplture around the campus. The 27 works are generally modern, created after 1970, by Irish artists.
points_of_interest.address: Stillorgan Road, Clonskeagh, County Dublin D04, Ireland

points_of_interest.name: Courtlough Adventure Centre
points_of_interest.description: Multi-activity centre for all ages, with high ropes, off-road buggies, paintball and zip lines. The Shooting Grounds have clay pigeon, rifle and archery. Advance booking essential.

points_of_interest.name: Belfield House
points_of_interest.description: Belfield House was the original estate purchased by UCD in the 1930s. It was built in 1801 by Ambrose Moore. Inside the porch (visible even if the house is locked) is one of the finest examples of Irish neoclassical sculpture called Hibernia, with the Bust of Lord Cloncurry. The sculpture was made by artist John Hogan in 1841 when he was working in Rome. The sculpture arrived in Ireland in 1846 to be exhibited at the Royal Exchange, which is now City Hall. The sculpture was in Lyons Estate and acquired by UCD when it purchased the estate in 1963. A large bay window (facing the running track) looks out onto Dublin Bay. Plasterwork found in the entrance hall and oval room is in Adams Style which is typical of Dublin houses of this time period. Current use for the house is as a reception for important visitors to the campus. Outside the house is a Loblolly pine tree, the state tree of the state of Arkansas in America. It was presented to former US President Bill Clinton when he visited to open the Clinton Institute for American Studies in 2010. Beside the house is the walled gardens.
points_of_interest.address: Stillorgan Road, Clonskeagh, County Dublin D04, Ireland

points_of_interest.name: Séamus Ennis Arts Centre
points_of_interest.description: A non-profit cultural centre dedicated to Séamus Ennis (1919-1982), the ''uilleann'' piper, folklore and music collector. Regular concerts and music classes, and excellent food.

points_of_interest.name: Drynam Park Driving Range
points_of_interest.description: Also offers lessons.

points_of_interest.name: Merville House
points_of_interest.description: This is the oldest house on the campus, built in 1750 by Anthony Foster who was chief baron of the Irish Exchequer. When he died the house was passed onto his son John who was the last speaker at the Irish House of Commons. Ownership then went to the Huge Dudgeons in 1890 and a riding school was established. The stables from the school were incorporated into the Nova centre.
points_of_interest.address: Stillorgan Road, Clonskeagh, County Dublin D04, Ireland

points_of_interest.name: Balheary Par 3
points_of_interest.description: Short 18-hole course of 2195 yards.

points_of_interest.name: Ardmore House
points_of_interest.description: Previously known as Belview and built in the 1800s as a country villa. Purchased in 1948 by the Department for Post and Telegraphs (predecessor to RTÉ television) which used it as a broadcasting station. UCD acquired Ardmore in 1957.r
points_of_interest.address: Road 9, Clonskeagh, County Dublin D04, Ireland

points_of_interest.name: St Margaret's Golf and Country Club
points_of_interest.description: Parkland course, black tees 6914 yards, par 73.
points_of_interest.address: Main Rd, St Margaret's K67 K339

points_of_interest.name: Woodview House
points_of_interest.description: Part of the Earl of Pembrokes Estate, built in 1820. Used to have a gatelodge, water streams, a footbridge and walled gardens. A wildflower meadow is opposite the house.

points_of_interest.name: Corrstown Golf Club
points_of_interest.description: This is a 27-hole course, 3 nines. The championship layout is twice around the Orchard course, blue tees 5638 m, par 70.

points_of_interest.name: University Lodge (Roebuck Grove)
points_of_interest.description: Residence of the President of UCD, with restoration completed in 2004 in-between presidents. House has a role as a reception venue with formal reception rooms with Greek facade and a rear section to the house for the President and his family.
points_of_interest.address: 34 Greenfield Park, Clonskeagh, County Dublin D04, Ireland

points_of_interest.name: Forrest Little Golf Club
points_of_interest.description: A mature parkland course, blue tees 5901 m, par 72.

points_of_interest.name: Richview
points_of_interest.description: Built in 1785 by the Powell family and originally a masonry boys school where students learned the art of masonry. UCD bought the estate in 1980 for €2.1 million and its buildings now house the School of Architecture, Planning and Environmental Policy. The main school building was once an orphanage for boys, while the quad was used for cricket matches and planted around it are lime trees. The Memorial Hall commemorates the students who died in World Wars I and II. It is now a lecture theatre, a choral scholars hall and an exhibition space. The adjacent Newstead is home to Leinster rugby and the campus's most mature trees (over 350 years old).
points_of_interest.address: Clonskeagh Drive, Clonskeagh, County Dublin D14, Ireland

points_of_interest.name: Kilronan Equestrian Centre
points_of_interest.description: It offers lessons and treks for all standards and ages.

points_of_interest.name: Newman Building
points_of_interest.description: The Newman Building is the largest single academic building on campus, housing the Arts, Humanities and Social Sciences colleges. It was designed by Andrzej Wejchert, who developed the original campus masterplan, and was the second purpose-built building on the campus, opening in 1970 as the Arts - Commerce - Law building. It has 7 floors, with 10 blocks containing classrooms, labs and offices (numbered A to K), and 7 large circular lecture theatres on the ground floor (numbered L to R). The top floor of block D provides a view across Dublin City and Dublin Bay. The building also houses the National Folklore Collection and the UCD Classics Museum.
points_of_interest.address: Road 9, Clonskeagh, County Dublin D04, Ireland

points_of_interest.name: Balheary Shooting
points_of_interest.description: This has two Olympic skeet ranges, two down-the-line ranges, 10 English sporting stands, Compak sporting and a {{feet|120}} tower.

points_of_interest.name: National Folklore Collection
points_of_interest.description: One of Europe’s largest archives of oral tradition and cultural history, and inscribed in 2017 to the UNESCO Memory of the World Register. Holds collections of manuscripts, Irish folk music, audio and video. Researchers are welcome to consult the Manuscript Collections without prior appointment, whilst researchers wishing to listen to audio recordings, view video material or to visit the Folk Music Collection should e-mail or telephone for an appointment.

points_of_interest.name: Sandymount Strand
points_of_interest.description: Large beach, with a grass promenade. Look out for the {{marker|name=Martello Tower| lat=53.32518 | long=-6.20690}} and the 20ft scuplture {{marker|name=Awaiting the Mariner (An Cailín Bán)| lat=53.32928 | long=-6.20863}}, donated by the Mexican president in 2002.

points_of_interest.name: Booterstown marsh
points_of_interest.description: {{ha|4.3}} salt marsh and mud nature reserve, with a viewing area at the northwestern corner. The marsh attracts a wide variety of birds.

points_of_interest.name: Guinness Storehouse
points_of_interest.description: Guinness is brewed in 49 countries and Ireland just happens to be one of them. The St James Gate brewery is still in production, now part of Diageo, and this vast storehouse has become an exhibition (self-guided) on the drink and the Guinness family. Price of entry includes a pint at the seventh floor Gravity Bar, which forms the head of the giant pint of stout formed by the atrium. Outside, touristy-trappy horse-drawn carriages ply for hire, but a stretch limo for the 2 km ride back to city centre might be cheaper.

points_of_interest.name: Teeling Distillery
points_of_interest.description: Distillery opened in 2015, primarily for whiskey but with small amounts of ''poitín''.

points_of_interest.name: Jameson Distillery
points_of_interest.description: Jameson whiskey was produced in Dublin from 1780 to 1976, when the business relocated to Midleton near Cork. So the old Bow St distillery no longer makes whiskey but has been converted into a museum about the process and industry.

points_of_interest.name: Abbey Theatre
points_of_interest.description: National Theatre of Ireland Opened in 1904, and always at the centre of the Irish drama scene, the Abbey is a good venue for catching local playwrights' work but with a global repertoire. It's intended to replace the current building with two new theatres fronting onto the Liffey. This will mean a lengthy closure, but the work has not started.

points_of_interest.name: Gaiety Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Founded in 1871 so this is the oldest continually operating theatre in Dublin. It hosts popular musical shows, opera, ballet, dance and drama.

points_of_interest.name: Gate Theatre
points_of_interest.description: This has a focus on European and American theatre ranging from classics to modern plays. It was established as a theatre company in 1928 by Hilton Edward and Micheál MacLiammóir.

points_of_interest.name: National Concert Hall
points_of_interest.description: This offers classical concerts. Frequent performances by the resident orchestra, the RTÉ National Symphony Orchestra. The main auditorium seats 1200 and there are three smaller spaces. It was built in 1865 for a trade fair then became an entertainment venue then the core of University College Dublin. It became a concert hall from 1981 when UCD moved to the Belfield campus.

points_of_interest.name: Bord Gáis Energy Theatre
points_of_interest.description: Grand Canal Theatre The theatre offers a wide range of shows featuring ballet, musicals, family shows, drama, concerts, comedy and opera. With a 2100-seater auditorium, the building was designed by Daniel Libeskind and completed in 2010.

points_of_interest.name: The Helix
points_of_interest.description: Event venue and theatre located in the northern suburbs of the city, built in 1996. Hosts a wide variety of talks and performances.
points_of_interest.address: DCU Glasnevin Campus, Collins Avenue D09 FW22

points_of_interest.name: Croke Park Stadium
points_of_interest.description: This stages Gaelic football and hurling for Dublin County GAA and national competitions, with a playing season April-Sep. The stadium has a capacity of 82,300 yet you may struggle to get tickets for big games. Tours of the stadium and [https://crokepark.ie/gaamuseum GAA museum] are also available, including a chance to try out these sports. You can also take the "skyline walk" across the stadium roof.

points_of_interest.name: Leinster Rugby
points_of_interest.description: Leinster play in the United Rugby Championship, the professional European league, and often win it. The stadium has a capacity of 18,500 and big games sometimes transfer to Aviva stadium.
points_of_interest.address: RDS Arena, Anglesea Rd, Ballsbridge D04 AK83

points_of_interest.name: Shamrock Rovers
points_of_interest.description: They play in the League of Ireland Premier Division, the top tier. The stadium (capacity 10,500) is on N81 two km west of M50.
points_of_interest.address: Tallaght Stadium, Whitestown Way D24 FNK6

points_of_interest.name: Leopardstown Racecourse
points_of_interest.description: This has regular meetings throughout the year, flat-racing in summer and jumps in winter. There's a "Pay as you Play" golf course within the racecourse grounds, as well as bars, restaurants and a nightclub.

points_of_interest.name: Irish Film Institute
points_of_interest.description: Arthouse cinema for independent Irish and international movies.
points_of_interest.address: 6 Eustace Street, Temple Bar D02 PD85

points_of_interest.name: Conradh na Gaeilge
points_of_interest.description: Gaelic League Cultural centre where Irish is the first language. They organise events and classes.

points_of_interest.name: GPO Museum
points_of_interest.description: The GPO is the headquarters of the Post Office in Ireland, built in Neo-Classical style 1814-1818. In 1916 it was occupied by Irish rebels led by PH Pearse, who read the Proclamation of the Republic outside the front door of the building. The interior was burnt out by shelling from government forces against the rebels, but the exterior survived. Subsequently the GPO was restored, reopening in 1929, and remains a busy working post office. The museum within it is a multimedia exploration of the Easter Rising.

points_of_interest.name: Dalkey Castle
points_of_interest.description: Goat Castle 14th-century fortified town house, with an 1890s extension that used to be the town hall. May-Oct there are "living history tours" with medieval characters, and guided walks several times a day.

points_of_interest.name: National Maritime Museum of Ireland
points_of_interest.description: Músaem Mhuirí Náisiúnta na hÉireann Housed within the former Mariner's Church. Exhibits include the Optic from the Bailey Lighthouse at Howth, MV Kerlogue a coastal vessel during World War II, the sinking of RMS Leinster in World War I, and the story of Captain Halpin of the Great Eastern.

points_of_interest.name: Howth Castle
points_of_interest.description: The castle dates from 1450 but was extensively re-built by Lutyens in 1911. The castle estate or ''desmesne'' includes much of Howth Head, with the outlying areas (eg the clifftop walks) having free public access. It's set in Deer Park, an extensive parkland with rhododendrons and a golf course. Since 2019 it's been closed for redevelopment as a hotel, but the castle cookery school has restarted. It's not known what will happen to the Transport Museum here.
points_of_interest.address: Harbour Road, Howth, County Dublin D13, Ireland

points_of_interest.name: Saints Peter & Paul Church
points_of_interest.description: Built in 1842, this RC church has two stained-glass windows by the Arts & Crafts exponent Harry Clarke: "The Widow's Son" left of the altar and "The Visitation" on the south wall. Mass is M-F at 10AM, plus noon in English and 3:30PM in Polish on Sunday.

points_of_interest.name: Malahide Castle
points_of_interest.description: The oldest parts of the castle are 12th century, though most of what you see is 18th / 19th century, richly furnished. It's set in a great parkland, the Malahide Demesne. Visit by guided tour only. Behind the castle are Talbot Botanic Gardens.
points_of_interest.address: Back Rd, Malahide Demesne K36 C432

points_of_interest.name: Swords Castle
points_of_interest.description: Built as a residence for the Archbishop of Dublin in the 13th century; not primarily defensive but a curtain wall encloses a large pentagonal courtyard. The building interiors are closed for interminable renovations, though group tours can be arranged. The surviving buildings include the northern tower (the Constable's residence), the chapel, and the southern gatehouse. The courtyard is open to visit and is often used for events, and the castle as a film and TV location.

points_of_interest.name: Festina Lente garden
points_of_interest.description: This is primarily an equestrian centre, but many visitors come for the two acre restored Victorian walled garden. Wonderful double herbaceous borders and vegetable allotments..
points_of_interest.address: Old Connaught Ave, Bray A98 F702

points_of_interest.name: Booterstown Martello Tower
points_of_interest.description: Coastal defence tower erected in 1804.
points_of_interest.address: Martello Terrace, Blackrock, County Dublin A94, Ireland

points_of_interest.name: St Mary's Pro-Cathedral
points_of_interest.description: Dublin's Catholic cathedral, built in 1825. Catholicism was always the majority religion in Ireland, but its practice was forbidden until the 19th century. The official cathedral is Christ Church, so designated by the Pope in 1300, but taken over by the Protestants in the 16th century. When the laws relaxed, St Mary's was built in neo-Classical style as a temporary or "pro"-cathedral, until such time as the Pope decrees otherwise or the Protestants hand back Christ Church. Neither event appears imminent.

points_of_interest.name: Joyce Tower Museum
points_of_interest.description: Túr agus Músaem Shéamuis Seoige The Martello tower with its gun platform and living quarters remain much as Joyce described it. The museum's collection includes letters, photographs, first and rare editions and personal possessions of Joyce as well as items associated with the Dublin of Leopold Bloom. First editions of most of Joyce's works are displayed, including the original ''Ulysses'' published in 1922. There's also one of two plaster death masks of Joyce by sculptor Paul Speck.

points_of_interest.name: National Transport Museum
points_of_interest.description: Volunteer-run museum with some 100 vehicles, including the trams which formerly lumbered over the Hill of Howth. It needs to find a better home, because the exhibits are tightly parked together, and Ireland's transport history deserves a better display.
points_of_interest.address: Heritage Depot, Howth Demesne D13 NF86

points_of_interest.name: Bremore Castle
points_of_interest.description: Scrappy remains of a tower house built in the 14th century, but falling into ruin in the 17th. It's closed for restoration.
points_of_interest.address: Drogheda Street, Balbriggan, County Dublin K32, Ireland

points_of_interest.name: Kilruddery House
points_of_interest.description: This vast pile has been the home of the Brabazons, Earls of Meath, for 350 years. The house was started in 1651 but extensively remodeled in neo-Tudor style in 1820-30, then scaled back in the 1960s. The formal garden (inspired by Versailles) was laid out in 1682, and is one of the few such gardens to survive the fashion for romantic naturalistic landscaping. The twin canals, known as the Long Ponds, are 152 m in length. House and grounds are often used as a film or TV location and may be booked out for weddings..
points_of_interest.address: Southern Cross Road, Kilruddery A98 W9F2
points_of_interest.hours: May-Sep Tu-Su 9:30AM-6PM, house tours at noon, 1:30PM, 3PM

points_of_interest.name: National Leprechaun Museum
points_of_interest.description: The "little folk" appeared in lore around 1300 AD but only flourished from the 19th century Celtic revival, dressed in late Georgian garb in an idealised rural past, mending a shoe. They proliferated into the silliest of 20th century Irish tourism, like greenfly upon the Rose of Tralee, and fell out of fashion. This museum is immersive telling of the stories woven around them, with a daytime and darker night show.

points_of_interest.name: Ardgillan Castle and Demesne
points_of_interest.description: The house, built in 1738, is set in extensive park lands overlooking the Irish Sea with a view of the Mourne Mountains. Guided tours take in the castle ground floor and kitchens. There are gardens, tea rooms, children’s playground, cycle and walking paths. In 2024 there's disruption from renovation, short-term closures, and tour prices are reduced.

points_of_interest.name: St Columba’s Church
points_of_interest.description: The Anglican church was built in Gothic style 1811-18 over a monastic settlement founded by St Colmcille / Columba. Its Round Tower, occasionally open in summer, is probably 9th century, and the square Clock Tower is 14th. The church was derelict for years but restored in 2022.
points_of_interest.address: Church Road, Swords Glebe K67 E447

points_of_interest.name: Hugh Lane Gallery
points_of_interest.description: Sir Hugh Lane (1875-1915) was one of the first collectors of modern art. He died in the sinking of ''Lusitania'' and this public gallery reflects his Will, which involved about as much negotiation, fudge and compromise as the Treaty for Irish independence. The permanent exhibitions are mostly contemporary Irish artists, plus Francis Bacon's studio, relocated from London in 2001. Charlemont House was built in 1763 and in 1929 its gardens were built over to create the gallery, which is wheelchair accessible.
points_of_interest.address: Charlemont House, Parnell Square North D01 F2X9

points_of_interest.name: St Colmcille’s Church
points_of_interest.description: RC church built in 1827 - at some peril, for although support for Catholic emancipation was gaining ground, the Penal Laws weren't repealed until 1829. The graveyard contains many interesting headstones, including one for Andrew Kettle (1833-1916), a key supporter of Parnell’s campaign for land reform. Another, to Patrick Carey who was only 30 when he died in 1879, has become enfolded by the tree planted at his grave.

points_of_interest.name: James Joyce Centre
points_of_interest.description: Georgian townhouse with an exhibition of Joyce's life and times. He never lived here himself.
points_of_interest.address: 35 North Great George's St D01 WK44

points_of_interest.name: Newbridge House & Farm
points_of_interest.description: Plush Georgian villa, built in 1747 for Charles Cobbe, Archbishop of Dublin. It remained in the Cobbe family until 1985, when they sold it to the County Council but are still resident. Entry by guided tour; this ticket also includes the Traditional Farm, which you can tour separately. There's also a walled garden, and extensive parkland (free, open daylight hours). Lanestown Castle is a scenic stump within the grounds.

points_of_interest.name: EPIC The Irish Emigration Museum
points_of_interest.description: Over the centuries more than 10 million people emigrated from Ireland; this is the story of why they left, where they went and how they shaped the world.
points_of_interest.address: CHQ, Custom House Quay D01 R9Y0

points_of_interest.name: The ''Jeanie Johnston''
points_of_interest.description: One million Irish people fled Ireland during the famine. 2500 took a gruelling voyage aboard the ''Jeanie Johnston'', and this is a replica. You take a 50 min tour above and below deck.

points_of_interest.name: Green on Red Gallery
points_of_interest.description: Commercial gallery exhibiting Irish and international modern art.
points_of_interest.address: Park Lane, Spencer Dock D01 Y821

points_of_interest.name: Outhouse LGBTQ+ Centre
points_of_interest.description: Safe space for LGBTQ+ people, with community café, social and cultural events, resources and support services, a queer library, theatre and meeting spaces.

points_of_interest.name: 14 Henrietta Street
points_of_interest.description: Many Dubliners lived in buildings like this. Built in the 1740s, its first occupant was Lord Viscount Molesworth and his family, and after him came a series of Right Honorable This and Viscount That and Bishop of Wherever. But the union with England in 1801 drained power and money to London, and the neighbourhood went downhill. Rural folk flocked to Dublin after the famine, so the building was broken up into tenements, with 100 living here. From the 1930s the inner city drained out to new suburbs, and No 14 fell derelict in 1970 before being preserved. Visit by guided tour.

points_of_interest.name: Trinity College
points_of_interest.description: Trinity College is the fine Georgian campus of the University of Dublin. It's generally open to stroll around in daylight hours, but it is a working university, and most interiors are off-limits to tourists. You can visit the Chapel near the front (west) gate of the College. But the big attraction is the '''Old Library and Book of Kells.''' Book online, otherwise buy your ticket from the machines under the Lecky library just south. This is for a timed slot, and at weekends may be booked out. You enter an exhibition hall setting the Book in the context of other monastic writings of its period, circa 800 AD. Next enter the display area: only two pages are displayed at any time, one being richly illustrated with little text (or no text, on the "carpet" pages), and one page being text of the Vulgate Gospels, written in Insular Majuscule Latin. But it's difficult to enjoy, with crowds jostling round the display case. Next, go upstairs into the massive Long Hall of the library, with books and ladders and more books and ladders towering away upwards. Last but not least, exit through the gift shop, which can be entered without a ticket.
points_of_interest.hours: Kells: May-Sep M-Sa 8:30AM-7PM, Su 9:30AM-5PM; Oct-Apr M-Sa 9:30AM-5PM, Su noon-4:30PM

points_of_interest.name: National Gallery of Ireland
points_of_interest.description: Impressive national collection of Irish and European Art. In January the gallery displays its watercolours by JMW Turner; the original donor specified that they had to be kept out of the light for the rest of the year.
points_of_interest.hours: Tu W F Sa 9:15AM-5:30PM, Th 9:15AM-8:30PM, Su M 11AM-5:30PM

points_of_interest.name: National Museum of Ireland - Archaeology
points_of_interest.description: Amazing display of Ireland's artefacts from prehistory through the Viking era to independence. The standout is the Treasury (with the 12th century Ardagh Chalice and 9th century Tara Brooch), and the prehistoric jewellery: gold and silver beautifully worked and carved - then chucked into the bog?? And likewise into the bog went bodies, presumably of defeated foes and heinous criminals given the violence of their deaths. Normally when a body is buried, the flesh decays and a skeleton persists. But if you throw a body into a peat bog, the acid dissolves the bones while tannin preserves the hide. The person turns into a handbag.

points_of_interest.name: Leinster House
points_of_interest.description: This opulent Georgian mansion is in the same block as the Archaeology Museum. Designed by Cassels, it was built in 1745 as the residence of the Duke of Leinster at a time when the southside was unfashionable. It proved an "anchor development" and Dublin's centre of power and culture soon gravitated from the northside. From 1922 it became the temporary base of the ''Oireachtas'', the Irish bi-cameral parliament, and like the Ulster border it remains temporary over a century later. Tours are only available if you're sponsored by a TD or senator.

points_of_interest.name: National Museum of Ireland - Natural History
points_of_interest.description: The "Dead Zoo" contains a comprehensive zoological collection presented in a manner unchanged since its establishment in Victorian times.

points_of_interest.name: Little Museum of Dublin
points_of_interest.description: Their main building on St Stephen's Green is closed for renovation, so this is a temporary home. It displays the 20th-century social, cultural and political history of Dublin city, with many artefacts donated by Dubliners. Visit by guided tour every hour.

points_of_interest.name: Irish Jewish Museum
points_of_interest.description: Exhibiting Jewish life in the cities - as in Great Britain, many were emigres from "White Russia". Their best known member is fictional, Leopold Bloom the protagonist of ''Ulysses''.

points_of_interest.name: Dublin Castle
points_of_interest.description: Former seat of British rule in Ireland. The guided tour takes in the medieval basements and Chapel Royal, then you see the State Apartments in your own time. You can skip the tour and just see the apartments for less.

points_of_interest.name: Christ Church Cathedral
points_of_interest.description: Holy Trinity A wooden church was built by the Vikings around 1030, and the first stone church was from the 1180s. So this is the oldest building in Dublin, though it underwent a massive restoration in the 1870s. It became Protestant under Henty VIII, apart from a brief Roman Catholic interlude in 1690 when the exiled James II was campaigning in Ireland, and the Vatican still claims it. The oldest part is the large crypt, where amongst the items on display are a mummified cat and rat, which got themselves stuck in the church organ in the 19th century.
points_of_interest.hours: Apr-Sep M-Sa 9:30AM-7PM, Su 12:30-14:30PM & 4:30-7PM; Oct-Mar M-Sa 9:30AM-5PM, Su 12:30-2:30PM

points_of_interest.name: Dublinia
points_of_interest.description: Viking Museum Exhibition of life in the Viking settlement and medieval city, child-friendly.

points_of_interest.name: St Patrick's Cathedral
points_of_interest.description: Founded in 1191, it became Anglican at the Reformation, so the Protestants had two cathedrals in the same city while the Catholics had none. It feuded with Christ Church over rights and precedence, until 1871 when Christ Church was nominated the senior church for Dublin and Glendalough and St Patrick's for the rest of Ireland. Jonathan Swift, author of ''Gulliver's Travels'', was dean of St Patrick's from 1713 to 1745 and is buried here, as is his lady friend Stella Johnson. It was rebuilt in the 1860s into a confident pile of Victoriana, and anything that looks medieval is probably a 19th century concoction.

points_of_interest.name: National Museum of Ireland - Decorative Arts & History
points_of_interest.description: The building is remarkable, a Georgian barracks around a parade square. Displays decorative arts and artefacts over 400 years, from rustic houses through Georgian elegance to "Proclaiming a Republic", the events of Easter 1916 when the interior decor of the Post Office took a sad turn for the worse.
points_of_interest.address: Collins Barracks, Benburb St D07 XKV4

points_of_interest.name: Irish Museum of Modern Art
points_of_interest.description: IMMA Modern and contemporary art, housed in the Royal Hospital of 1684. See also the elegant courtyard and formal gardens.
points_of_interest.address: Royal Hospital, Military Road, Kilmainham D08 FW31

points_of_interest.name: Kilmainham Gaol
points_of_interest.description: This prison was in use 1796-1924; thousands have passed through, including many convicts transported to Australia. It's best known as the place where the rebels from the 1916 Easter Rising were executed. (Several now lie in Arbour Hill Cemetery just north of the Decorative Arts Museum.) Access by guided tour every 30 min, pre-booking essential.

points_of_interest.name: Dublin Zoo
points_of_interest.description: Opened in 1830 and extended in 1997, this Zoo has a dozen habitats and is the largest in Ireland.

points_of_interest.name: Rathfarnham Castle
points_of_interest.description: Built as a fortified mansion around 1583 and prettified in the 18th century, it fell derelict in the 19th but has been restored as a museum.

points_of_interest.name: Pearse Museum
points_of_interest.description: Patrick Pearse (1879-1916) saw Irish culture and language as essential for national independence. His one and only case as a barrister was his unsuccessful defence of a Donegal tradesman for using an "illegible" sign, and the verdict effectively made Irish signage illegal. He set up a language school in 1908, which moved here in 1910. He was also a leading Republican, reading the proclamation of independence on the GPO steps in the Easter Rising of 1916. He was court-martialled and shot nine days later.
points_of_interest.address: St Enda's Park, Rathfarnham D16 Y7Y5

points_of_interest.name: Glasnevin Cemetery
points_of_interest.description: Reilig Ghlas Naíon This opened as an RC cemetery in 1832, in an era when the Catholics weren't allowed their own parish churches, and their burials were begrudged affairs in Protestant ground. Glasnevin has grown and grown, expanding south across Finglas road into the St Paul's section, but the famous names are north side. You can visit the cemetery free, but to make sense of it go to the visitor centre (daily 10AM-5PM, closed M Tu in winter). Walking tours visit the graves of Daniel O'Connell, Charles Stewart Parnell, Michael Collins, Eamonn De Valera and many others of historic or architectural interest. A back gate connects to the Botanic Gardens.

points_of_interest.name: National Botanic Gardens
points_of_interest.description: Extensive gardens favouring alkaline-loving species. The great Palm House was where Wittgenstein often came to warm his lugubrious backside. A gateway leads into Glasnevin Cemetery adjacent. The gardens also manage the arboretum at Kilmacurragh near Wicklow Town.
points_of_interest.hours: Mar-Oct M-F 9AM-5PM, Sa Su 10AM-6PM; Nov-Feb M-F 9AM-4:30PM, Sa Su 10AM-4:30PM

points_of_interest.name: Thyme Out
points_of_interest.description: Deli grocery with sandwiches, breads, cakes and other tasty things.

points_of_interest.name: Gutter Bookshop
points_of_interest.description: Small bookshop but good selection, knowledgeable staff.

points_of_interest.name: RNLI Shop
points_of_interest.description: Official gift shop for the Royal National Lifeboat Institute.

points_of_interest.name: Cornelscourt Shopping Centre
points_of_interest.description: Contains a large Dunnes Stores (food, clothes, off-license and homeware), an optician, café, hair salon, pharmacy and newsagents. Free indoor and outdoor parking.

points_of_interest.name: Swords Pavilions
points_of_interest.description: This is the main shopping centre, one block back from Main Street. The largest shops are Dunnes Stores, Superquinn, TK Maxx, Zara, H&M and River Island.

points_of_interest.name: Merrion Centre
points_of_interest.description: The Merrion Centre is a shopping centre situated at the junction of Nutley Lane with Merrion Road. It is anchored by the Tesco supermarket and the Japanese embassy is located in the centre.

points_of_interest.name: Brown Thomas
points_of_interest.description: Dublin's best-known and expensive department store.

points_of_interest.name: Kilkenny Design
points_of_interest.description: Clothing, jewellery and giftware.

points_of_interest.name: Hodges Figgis
points_of_interest.description: Well-stocked large bookshop, part of the Waterstones chain.

points_of_interest.name: Powerscourt Centre
points_of_interest.description: Attractive shopping centre in a beautifully restored 18th-century townhouse, with clothes, cafes, galleries and jewellers. You're paying premium prices for the elegant location.

points_of_interest.name: George's Street Arcade
points_of_interest.description: Market Arcade A covered red-brick shopping arcade, with vintage clothing, fabrics, unusual accessories, vinyl and club wear. It also has some small cafes.

points_of_interest.name: Arnott's
points_of_interest.description: A large department store with a long history.

points_of_interest.name: Jervis Shopping Centre
points_of_interest.description: Shopping centre with some 50 stores.

points_of_interest.name: Chapters Bookstore
points_of_interest.description: Huge selection of books at keen prices, as well as a large secondhand section.
points_of_interest.address: Ivy Exchange, Parnell Street D01 P8C2

points_of_interest.name: Fitzpatrick Castle Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Upmarket hotel on the hill above Killiney, with restaurant and small pool.
points_of_interest.address: Killiney Hill Rd, Scalpwilliam, Killiney A96 N125

points_of_interest.name: Grand Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Splendid old 4-star on the coast, often hosts weddings and other events.

points_of_interest.name: Strand Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Comfy, small hotel in mansion built by the parents of Oscar Wilde, and inherited by him in 1876. Each of the 10 rooms is named for one of his works, so decide whether you want to be An Ideal Husband or Lady Windermere's Fan. Presumably the Canterville Ghost can access all rooms..

points_of_interest.name: Malahide Guest Rooms
points_of_interest.description: Comfy guesthouse, no catering, 500 m south of village centre.

points_of_interest.name: The Palm
points_of_interest.description: Comfy hotel on the seafront, good restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: White Sands Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Simple but good value hotel with 58 rooms in Portmarnock. Decent food, live music in the bar.

points_of_interest.name: Gleann-na-Smoi
points_of_interest.description: Small, homely B&B south end of town.

points_of_interest.name: Marine Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Comfy hotel with its lawn rolling down to the shore of Dublin Bay. Facilities include a swimming pool, sauna, restaurants and bar. Close to Howth Village.

points_of_interest.name: Haddington House
points_of_interest.description: Charming small hotel at the foot of East Pier, a knock-through of 19th century townhouses.

points_of_interest.name: Bracken Court Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Renovated in 2024, clean and near beach and town centre. With restaurant, but they've scrapped the Sunday carvery.

points_of_interest.name: Rochestown Lodge Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Smart modern hotel with spa and leisure centre, mostly good reviews.

points_of_interest.name: Woodview Farmhouse
points_of_interest.description: Welcoming B&B just south of Ardgillan Castle.

points_of_interest.name: CityNorth Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Business hotel at jcn 7 of M1, just over the boundary into Co Meath. It often hosts business conferences and might break a journey north.

points_of_interest.name: Radisson Blu St. Helen's Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A grand house and gardens built in the 1750s which became a hotel in 1998.

points_of_interest.name: Forty Four Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Pleasant hotel with 14 rooms in town centre. Some noise from the pub, open to 11PM.

points_of_interest.name: Travelodge Dublin Airport North
points_of_interest.description: Reliable budget chain with comfy rooms, 500 m south of Swords Main Street. Parking €5 per night during stay, no long-stay parking. It's on bus route 41 to the airport and central Dublin.
points_of_interest.address: Pinnock Hill Roundabout, Swords K67 K6R2

points_of_interest.name: Premier Inn Dublin Airport
points_of_interest.description: Reliable comfy budget chain. It's called "Dublin Airport" but is closer to Swords, about 1 km south of town centre. Parking €10 a day during stay, but no long-stay parking. A shuttle bus runs every 30 min between hotel and airport.
points_of_interest.address: Airside Retail Park, Swords K67 E4A6

points_of_interest.name: San Augustine B&B
points_of_interest.description: Pleasant B&B in detached modern town house. Five minutes walk to Swords.

points_of_interest.name: Evergreen B&B
points_of_interest.description: Friendly well-run B&B 3 km north of Swords.

points_of_interest.name: Seamount House
points_of_interest.description: Comfortable friendly guesthouse in quiet cul de sac on the east edge of Swords, 1 km from town centre. No credit cards.
points_of_interest.address: 18 Seamount View, Malahide Rd, Swords K67 Y778

points_of_interest.name: Tirconaill
points_of_interest.description: Pleasant guesthouse (room only) close to centre of Swords. Free parking at the rear of the house.
points_of_interest.address: 2 Longlands, Malahide Rd, Swords K67 V832

points_of_interest.name: Kettle's Country House Hotel
points_of_interest.description: This countryside hotel has 25 bedrooms and a range of special events facilities. With restaurant and bar food.

points_of_interest.name: Roganstown Hotel and Country Club
points_of_interest.description: Plush hotel and Country Club out in the rolling hills. Facilities include restaurant, bar, leisure centre, pool, 18 hole golf course, wedding and conference venues and free car parking. Shuttle bus available to Swords or airport.

points_of_interest.name: Camac Valley Caravan and Camping Park
points_of_interest.description: Friendly well-run site on bus route to city.

points_of_interest.name: Abbey Court Hostel
points_of_interest.description: Clean well-run hostel just off O'Connell St.

points_of_interest.name: Ashling House
points_of_interest.description: Basic accommodation in leafy Drumcondra. Decent rooms but it's not a B&B.

points_of_interest.name: Jacobs Inn
points_of_interest.description: Nice, clean budget hostel with keycard security. Ensuite shower and bathroom as well as an additional washroom at the end of each hall. The bunks are pods so there's extra privacy.

points_of_interest.name: Lyndon House
points_of_interest.description: Basic but clean B&B near the James Joyce Museum and the Custom House.

points_of_interest.name: Albany House
points_of_interest.description: Good central 3-star, some noise in street-facing rooms. Shower and taps take 5 min to run hot, keep running and have faith.

points_of_interest.name: Ariel House
points_of_interest.description: Comfy welcoming B&B near Aviva stadium. No dogs.

points_of_interest.name: Belvedere Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Swish hotel in a Georgian townhouse.

points_of_interest.name: Clayton Hotel Ballsbridge
points_of_interest.description: Splendid hotel in 19th-century school building, 3 km south of centre. They have three other hotels in town and one at the airport.

points_of_interest.name: Buswells Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Cosy Georgian hotel, small rooms but friendly staff, good location.

points_of_interest.name: Castle Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Welcoming Georgian hotel with 130 bedrooms all en suite. Restaurant & bar with live Irish music every weekend.

It won an architectural award so it's probably a mercy that it's screened by mature trees. Just to make sure, they put one within, a Himalayan cedar in the courtyard. The County Council have a branch office in Blanchardstown.

pois.name: Leinster House
pois.description: This opulent Georgian mansion is in the same block as the Archaeology Museum. Designed by Cassels, it was built in 1745 as the residence of the Duke of Leinster at a time when the southside was unfashionable. It proved an "anchor development" and Dublin's centre of power and culture soon gravitated from the northside. From 1922 it became the temporary base of the ''Oireachtas'', the Irish bi-cameral parliament, and like the Ulster border it remains temporary over a century later. Tours are only available if you're sponsored by a TD or senator.

pois.name: 14 Henrietta Street
pois.description: Many Dubliners lived in buildings like this. Built in the 1740s, its first occupant was Lord Viscount Molesworth and his family, and after him came a series of Right Honorable This and Viscount That and Bishop of Wherever. But the union with England in 1801 drained power and money to London, and the neighbourhood went downhill. Rural folk flocked to Dublin after the famine, so the building was broken up into tenements, with 100 living here. From the 1930s the inner city drained out to new suburbs, and No 14 fell derelict in 1970 before being preserved. Visit by guided tour.
